<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[227,286,1170,1196]" box="[227,286,1170,1196]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,286,1170,1196]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,286,1170,1196]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Note</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[227,1437,1217,1525]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The question of whether the moss-feeding 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Borner" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[739,900,1217,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Muscaphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="escherichi">
<emphasis box="[739,900,1217,1243]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">M. escherichi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents the secondary host generations of the 
<taxonomicName box="[271,352,1252,1278]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Sorbus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[271,352,1252,1278]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Sorbus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-feeding 
<taxonomicName authority="(Borner, 1939)" baseAuthorityName="Borner" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[458,890,1252,1278]" class="Bryopsida" family="Mniaceae" genus="Mnium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="drepanosiphoides">
<emphasis box="[458,706,1252,1278]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">M. drepanosiphoides</emphasis>
(Börner, 1939)
</taxonomicName>
, which would make the two taxa synonymous (
<bibRefCitation author="Blackman R. L. &amp; Eastop V. F." box="[235,542,1287,1314]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref10635" refString="Blackman R. L. &amp; Eastop V. F. 2014. Aphids on the World's plants. Available from http: // www. aphidsonworldsplants. info / [accessed on 13 Feb. 2015]." type="url" year="2014">Blackman &amp; Eastop 2014</bibRefCitation>
), has not yet been definitely resolved, and is awaiting results from molecular analyses. Until then, I prefer to continue regarding the two taxa as separate species, because they are morphologically distinctive. Among other characteristics are the siphunculi, which are generally quite constant throughout the parthenogenetic morphs. In the 
<taxonomicName box="[902,983,1393,1419]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Sorbus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[902,983,1393,1419]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Sorbus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-feeding fundatrix and alatae they are long, black and truncate, with a large terminal aperture. The transfer experiments of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Borner" baseAuthorityYear="1939" box="[1192,1437,1428,1454]" class="Bryopsida" family="Mniaceae" genus="Mnium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bryales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="drepanosiphoides">
<emphasis box="[1192,1437,1428,1454]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">M. drepanosiphoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName box="[294,375,1463,1489]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Sorbus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[294,375,1463,1489]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Sorbus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName box="[420,682,1463,1489]" class="Bryopsida" family="Plagiotheciaceae" genus="Plagiothecium" kingdom="Fungi" order="Hypnales" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="laetum">
<emphasis box="[420,682,1463,1489]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Plagiothecium laetum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
performed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stekolshchikov A. V. &amp; Shaposhnikov G. Kh." box="[865,1345,1463,1489]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="42 - 54" refId="ref11380" refString="Stekolshchikov A. V. &amp; Shaposhnikov G. Kh. 1993. [Revision of the genus Muscaphis ….] Entomologicheskoe Obozrenie 72: 333 - 344. [English translation (1994) Entomological Review 73: 42 - 54]" type="journal article" year="1993">Stekolshchikov &amp; Shaposhnikov (1993)</bibRefCitation>
would, however, give support for the synonymy.
</paragraph>
